This paper deals with regular languages and their quotient complexities, which are fundamental concepts in formal language theory. Therefore, cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and the use of binomial coefficients, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper discusses upper bounds on the quotient complexity of atoms of regular languages, which could be relevant to researchers in cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
